[3] Kathmandu, Nepal: suspected case - hospital report
Date: Sat 18 Jan 2020
From: Dr. Sher Bahadur Pun <drsherbdr@yahoo.com> [edited]


Suspected 2019-nCoV case, Kathmandu, Nepal
------------------------
On [13 Jan 2020] a 31-year-old male with no chronic disease sought medical care for high-grade fever, shortness of breath, and dry cough after his return from Wuhan, China. In fact, he had gradually developed these symptoms since [5 Jan 2020], before his departure (from Wuhan, China). According to the WHO case definition, the patient was suspected of having 2019-nCoV and therefore kept under close observation. These symptoms lasted for 10 days. He was discharged without further complications. This novel virus, however, was not confirmed by specific laboratory testing until the day of his discharge [see comment below for further clarification].

The patient denied having visited seafood or live animal markets in Wuhan that linked to this outbreak, which is, at present, widely believed to be the source of 2019-nCoV, indicating that this novel coronavirus virus may [be] capable of human-to-human transmission. Usually cough triggers breathing difficulties, but conversely, he complained of dry cough followed by difficulty in breathing. Although we do not know about its exact origin, dynamic transmission, spectrum of disease, mortality rate, preventive measures, and possible global impact, it is wise to remain vigilant against this virus in the coming days.

--
Dr. Sher Bahadur Pun
Sukraraj Tropical & Infectious Disease Hospital
<drsherbdr@yahoo.com>

[Our thanks to Dr. Sher Bahadur Pun for this report on the suspected case of pneumonia related to infection with the 2019 nCoV. Per follow-up with Dr. Pun, "the test itself is not available in Nepal. Thus the patient's samples [must be sent] abroad to confirm the virus. Hence the case, so far, remains suspected (clinically and epidemiologically) with no laboratory confirmation."

This report serves to demonstrate the extent of international travel in today's day and age and the level of surveillance ongoing internationally in response to the reports of this outbreak, and importations of infected cases into other countries.

HealthMap/ProMED map:
Nepal: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=6897282,139
- Mod.MPP]

