Methods
Using internationally reported cases, it is possible to infer the magnitude of comparable cases within Wuhan City that may have occurred thus far.

The total number of cases requiring healthcare is given by:

the total number of cases is equal to the number of cases detected overseas divided by the probability any one case will be detected overseas,

where the probability any one case will be detected overseas (p) is given by:

p = daily probability of international travel x mean time to detection of a case.

The daily probability of travel is calculated by:

the daily probability of international travel equals the daily outbound number of international travellers from Wuhan divided by the catchment population of Wuhan airport.

Finally, the mean time to detection can be approximated by:

mean time to detection equals incubation period plus time from onset of symptoms to detection.

Confidence intervals can be calculated from the observation that the number of cases detected overseas, X, is binomially distributed as Bin(p,N), where p equals the probability any one case will be detected overseas, and N is the total number of cases. N is therefore a negative binomially distributed function of X. The results in Table 1 are maximum-likelihood estimates obtained using this negative binomial likelihood function.

